loc: Bunken Plantage, Hulsig, Frederikshavn Municipality, North Denmark Region
rmk: Flock of c 30 in spruce trees.

Feeding on ornamental Spruces (Picea pungens). The flock was disturbed by something (as was nearby Red-breasted Nuthatches) and they circled for about a minute before returning to feeding. The recording was made on an Olympus LS10 linear PCM microphone and was high-pass filtered at 1000 Hz with 12 dB/Hz roll-off to eliminate the noise of ventilation from a nearby building. The recording was then normalized so that the maximum volume was -1 dB.

forest near Hagenheim/Hofstetten (near Landsberg), Upper Bavaria, Bavaria
type: call, flight call, very excited calls
rmk:
In this winter there are a lot of Crossbills in our region. Today morning I heard in the nearby wood these calls in the top of high spruces.  I am not familiar with the voices of young Crossbills and I first thought, it could be the begging calls of fledged Crossbills. Specially, because I heard long series of these calls in short intervalls. But the discussion in the forum convinced me, that these calls (which I never heard before) are probably exciting calls of adult Crossbills. Mating? Or because a hawk was roaming through the wood?  But why in relatively regular Intervalls? Same place, same situation look at XC304228, XC304229, XC302839.
At 0:19 "normal" flight calls from an adult. 
Weather: relatively warm since long, the spruces have a lot of cones.

rmk: Weather: light rain after a frosty night. The bird is singing in a street tree for at least six minutes. A big garden is near, the wood in a distance from about 200 m  -  in this area it seems to breed, because I see and hear here Crossbills every day. loc: Bay Bulls, Division No. 1, Newfoundland and Labrador
rmk: This was my first success in recording the flight calls of this Newfoundland type 8 Red Crossbill. The quality is marginal as I was using my Sony PCM D-50 with built in mics rather than a directional mic. Still, I was recording from just a few feet away from a flock of ten or so birds.

loc: Pike National Forest (near  Woodland Park), El Paso County, Colorado
type: alarm call, female, flight call, male, recordist noise, wind
rmk: Mated pair of type 5 in extensive Lodgepole Pine forest. Observed foraging for over 30 minutes primarily (~90%) on weathered (gray) serotinous cones, the other 10% of foraging on new non-serotinous cones. Pair flew up to the top of an adjacent Lodgepole and started giving alarm calls in response to pishing.

loc: Montaña de Izopo, Sector Las Moras
rmk: A female giving calls from a tall dead tree, perched near the top at approximately 18 m high. Halfway in the recording, a male can be heard calling, at first from afar and then equally close (perched in the same tree at more or less the same height, 5 m between them). The second half of the recording has his calls, not hers, although she was still there. His calls are similar doubled notes, but slightly lower-pitched.
